<TEXT>
while irish citizens find it difficult to immigrate 
to the united states hundreds of americans in recent years have 
taken advantage of irish laws that make it relatively easy to claim 
irish citizenship 
americans who become irish citizens can easily establish 
residency in ireland obtain an irish passport or gain access to the 
11 other countries of the european community 
but nostalgia seems to be the main reason many americans seek a 
link to the emerald isle officials say 
i think the majority of people do this out of a sense really 
of their irish heritage said declan kelleher spokesman for the 
irish embassy in washington 
kelleher said interest in dual citizenship was negligible until 
about seven years ago since 1985 about 4100 americans have 
claimed their irish citizenship about 1300 from the boston area 
this year 600 nationwide have applied 400 to the consulate in new 
york 
foreigners have been able to claim irish citizenship since 1956 
one of those to apply this year was bob mccarthy of lewiston 
idaho his grandparents came from ireland and soon after landing in 
boston in the 1890s they moved to work at a montana smelter 
mccarthy a lawyer said he hopes to live in ireland some day to 
gain a new perspective on americas history 
i think that its helpful in terms to understand where you 
come from and in terms of knowing yourself he said by telephone 
and i think the ethnicity of people in the united states is an 
important element that shouldnt be forgotten 
obtaining dual citizenship does not jepoardize ones us 
citizenship as long as the second country does not require any 
superseding oath of allegiance said phil covington of the state 
departments consular bureau 
ireland israel the united kingdom italy and canada are the 
five countries from which most americans obtain dual citizenship 
embassies for the other countries could not provide figures 
they are generally places that dont make it difficult to 
obtain or require a strong oath of allegiance which would make it 
difficult for an american to obtain citizenship he said 
although rules vary from country to country an american 
generally must have a blood tie or birthright to claim citizenship 
from a foreign country 
countries from which it is difficult to obtain dual citizenship 
are mexico spain austria and germany they require new citizens 
to renounce old allegiances 
in 1986 the irish citizenship law was tightened the rules are 
as follows 
anyone whose parents were born in ireland is automatically an 
irish citizen and simply needs to register with the embassy or a 
consulate 
grandchildren of people born in ireland must prove their link 
by presenting their birth certificates and those of their ancestors 
or other documentation a 153 registration fee is also required 
beyond that a family can continue to evoke the right but there 
is one provision kelleher said and that is that at the time of 
the birth of whoever chooses to invoke that right their parents 
were already irish citizens 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890908-0011 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the navy said thursday that gunners mate 
clayton hartwig most likely caused the explosion that killed 47 
sailors aboard the uss iowa by shoving a detonator between gunpowder 
bags in one of the battleships huge guns 
the formal report on the explosion the worst naval disaster 
since the vietnam war said the exact cause cannot be pinpointed 
since the sailors close enough to see what was going on including 
hartwig were all killed in the fiery blast 
however rear adm richard milligan presenting the official 
conclusions at a pentagon briefing said much circumstantial 
information pointed to hartwig whose job put him closest to the 
gun 
he cited an fbi psychological profile of hartwig with the 
opinion that he took his own life and hoped it looked like an 
accident 
members of hartwigs family strongly disputed the navy 
conclusion family lawyer kreig j brusnahan said dead men cant 
defend themselves the navy knows that 
milligan said hartwig was a loner and a man with low 
selfesteem who had a series of male principal friends 
throughout his life but the admiral and other military briefers 
said there is no substantive proof that hartwig was homosexual 
and there is no mention of that in the report 
adm leon edney the vice chief of naval operations said of 
hartwig he was a cleancut sailor he didnt smoke he didnt 
drink he didnt carouse on leave he wasnt a troublemaker 
we dont know the motivation edney said 
the navy admirals said investigators extensively questioned 
hartwigs acquaintances and family after the explosion 
after more than four months of investigation the navy concluded 
the explosion was most probably caused by an intentional act the 
weight of evidence indicates that some type of detonation device was 
deliberately placed between the powder bags being rammed into the 
breech of the center gun 
as evidence the investigators cited foreign material found 
on the projectile that remained in the gun barrel after the 
explosion milligan said the navys tests showed that a detonation 
device apparently was placed between the first and second bags of 
gunpowder and that it could have been composed of such simple 
elements as bleach brake fluid and steel wool 
the most likely person with the access knowledge and possible 
motivation to accomplish this act has been identified as gunners 
mate 2nd class clayton m hartwig usn the center gun captain in 
turret ii at the time of the explosion the navy said 
milligan said no accidental cause could be found and a criminal 
investigation was launched after hartwigs sister kathy kubicina 
disclosed the existence of a 100000 accidental death and 
dismemberment policy on her brothers life naming gunners mate 3rd 
class kendall truitt as a beneficiary 
the navys conclusions were immediately disputed by hartwigs 
relatives who have asked for a separate congressional investigation 
i never believed it right from the start said his sister 
who attended a briefing by navy officials at her fathers home in 
cleveland 
earl hartwig the dead sailors father said i think there was 
a powder explosion accidental that caused the explosion 
truitt one of the crew who survived the blast in the lowest 
level of the massive gun turret has demanded an apology from the 
navy contending it leaked information about the investigation to 
the news media in order to find a scapegoat edney rejected the idea 
of an apology 
at a news conference in miami truitts attorney ellis rubin 
dismissed the navys version of the explosion saying our 
information was that it was the navys negligence untrained and 
unqualified crew members and 50yearold technology dangerous from 
day one 
the navy report found numerous lapses in the recordkeeping of 
the gun crews training the requirements for handling the world war 
iivintage ships weapons and safety procedures 
but the navy said these shortcomings did not cause the 
explosion 
the report said investigators found that hartwig had experimented 
with explosive devices and detonators had frequently talked about 
dying and had a fascination with ship disasters 
the investigators said hartwig had recently had a fallingout 
with an extremely close friend and that on the night before the 
explosion his attempts at a close relationship with another 
sailor had been rejected 
the navy in its 1100page report said the investigation had 
ruled out technical failure or an accidental cause for the april 19 
blast 
investigators said hartwig as the gun captain was responsible 
for overseeing the loading of the 16inch gun during the 
battleships gunnery exercises some 330 miles from puerto rico 
the report said he could have hidden a small homemade detonating 
device in a pack that is normally placed between the bags of powder 
and helps clean the barrel out after the explosion 
hartwig was positioned at the breech of the gun meaning that he 
would have been the first killed when the massive force of the 
explosion blew backwards through the open barrel and into the 
sevenstory gun turret 
the navy officials noted that the reports conclusions about 
hartwig were based on circumstantial evidence but they contended 
that this evidence combined with an exhaustive fbi and naval 
investigative service studies of the blast supported their theories 
the 4 million navy investigation involved interviews with more 
than 318 people and 20000 tests some trying to simulate the 
explosion 
only 11 survivors none nearby lived through the fireball which 
tore through the no 2 or middle gun turret the 16inch weapons 
aboard the battleship can fire 2700 pound shells a distance of 23 
miles 
each projectile is propelled by explosives loaded into the gun 
barrel contained in silk bags the gun usually requires up to six 
bags each containing about 100 pounds of black gunpowder 
the investigators said the foreign material that was found in the 
gun should not have been there under normal firing conditions 
they also said their tests showed that an exact replica of the 
explosion could only have occurred if a detonating device had been 
placed between the first and second bags of gunpowder such a device 
could have gone off when the rammer supposedly directed by hartwig 
pushed the silk bags of powder together in the guns barrel 
the ships commander capt fred p moosally the ships 
executive officer weapons officer and gunnery officer are all 
expected to be called to explain onboard proceedural lapses in a 
hearing that could determine whether any punishment will be meted 
out 
the milligan report recommended charges against five individuals 
whose names were blanked out appropriate administrative action 
to caution three people including the executive officer of the 
ship with respect to duties removal of the gunnery officer 
and the weapons officer from their jobs and administrative or 
disciplinary action against another person one recommendation not 
approved by the chief of naval operations 
the endorsement by the chief of naval operations concurred in a 
recommendation by the commander of surface forces atlantic fleet 
that the captain and executive officer not be subject to judicial 
action or removal but the navys chief directed that special 
reprimands be prepared for them 
in a statement released at the pentagon moosally said he 
accepted the conclusion that the explosion was caused by an 
intentional act and he said he took full responsibility for any 
shortcomings found aboard his ship and had no excuses for them 
saying all administrative problems have been corrected the 
captain praised his crews efforts in helping recover from the 
disaster we are relieved that the investigation is now complete 
