<TEXT>
given the drugrelated violence wracking 
colombia can the united states take adequate security precautions 
to keep extradited drug kingpins in jail 
the marshals service and the bureau of prisons say they can 
they contend the handling of convicted medellin drug cartel 
leader carlos lehder rivas proves their ability to keep 
highvisibility drug traffickers in prison 
this week the colombian government extradited eduardo martinez 
romero wanted on moneylaundering and drugtrafficking charges 
leveled in march in atlanta martinez who arrived in atlanta early 
thursday is the first person brought to the united states under a 
newly reinstituted extradition agreement 
attorney general dick thornburgh says the country must face up to 
the task of providing security in drugtrafficking cases despite 
the possibility of attacks 
we cant succumb in this country to what has already brought 
the criminal justice system to its knees in colombia thornburgh 
said when he recently announced the list of the top 12 alleged drug 
traffickers the united states wants to bring here to stand trial 
including the leaders of the notorious medellin and cali cartels 
the marshals service handled the security for the transport and 
trial of lehder who was extradited in 1987 and convicted july 20 
1988 in jacksonville fla he is in federal prison in marion ill 
serving a life sentence without parole plus 140 years 
although the colombian supreme court revoked the extradition 
agreement two years ago president virgilio barco reinstituted it 
under emergency measures after the aug 18 assassination of leading 
presidential candidate luis carlos galan an outspoken foe of the 
drug trade 
the justice department attempted to prevent any information about 
the martinez extradition from getting out even after the news was 
broadcast in colombia 
department spokesman david runkel said thursday that concern 
about security prompted the clampdown on information even after 
the dea confirmed that martinez was in the air heading toward the 
united states 
bill dempsey spokesman for the marshals service which takes 
custody of people extradited to the united states said that if any 
of the top 12 are extradited every effort would be made to 
provide all the necessary security and the resources would be 
obtained to provide the security for the extradition of the 
individuals 
dempsey said he was unsure how much it cost to provide security 
for lehder who was convicted on charges of conspiracy to import 
cocaine importation of cocaine possession with intention to 
distribute cocaine and operating a continuing criminal enterprise 
he arrived at prison aug 5 1988 
randy davis a spokesman for the marion penitentiary said 
lehders ties to the medellin cartel have not prompted any 
additional security measures by the prisons 215 corrections 
officers 
this being the most maximumsecurity penitentiary in the 
federal prison system it doesnt require us to add any additional 
security here he said it was always present that was the 
reason for his designation to this facility 
lehder doesnt present a remarkably greater threat to security 
than the other 435 or so prisoners at marion he said 
we have a lot of highprofile highpublicity inmates with a 
lot of money doing a great deal of time davis said 
lehder like all the other inmates there has a cell to himself 
and he prefers to remain alone even when he gets out of the cell for 
one hour of recreation per day davis said only about 20 inmates 
are allowed in the recreation yard at a time he said 
davis said he couldnt disclose who was on lehders visiting list 
and said he didnt know if lehder had had any visitors but he added 
that any visitors would have to be checked out to ensure that there 
are no security problems 
it wouldnt be very smart for them to come here if theyre part 
of the medellin cartel davis said 
he noted that all visits except for those with attorneys are 
noncontact meetings 
