<DOCNO> AP890908-0037 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
depletion of ozone in the skies above may lead 
to sick and dying plants on the earth below according to studies by 
a us department of agriculture researcher 
autar k mattoo leader of the usdas plant molecular biology lab 
in beltsville md said ultravioletb radiation or uvb the 
solar rays that give people tans and skin cancer will destroy half 
of a plants store of a critical photosynthesis protein every half 
hour 
the plant is able to restore the protein and continue 
photosynthesis when it receives normal levels of uvb radiation 
mattoo said but at higher levels of uvb the plant would be 
stripped of the protein and photosynthesis would stop 
in a few hours time you would have hardly any of this protein 
left in the plant he said thursday in a telephone interview 
the plant would wither away and die 
mattoo said that based on his studies an increase in uvb also 
could weaken and kill some plants 
experiments in beltsville and israel showed that uvb causes a 
breakdown of a plant molecule called d1 protein that protein he 
said is an essential component in the photochemistry that enables 
plants to convert sunlight into chemical energy a process called 
photosynthesis 
the plant does try to replenish the molecules mattoo said 
but if you have higher uvb radiation the plant will not keep up 
with the molecules that are being destroyed thats when we think 
there will be an effect on photosynthesis 
such an impact on the normal growth of agricultural crops would 
inevitably lead to a smaller harvest and less food he said 
uvb is a normal component of sunlight most of the radiation is 
filtered out by ozone in the earths stratosphere and never reaches 
the ground but recent studies have shown that some types of 
pollution are causing the ozone layer to thin in places creating 
what scientists called ozone holes 
experts are concerned that a thin ozone layer would allow enough 
additional uvb to reach the earths surface to cause a rise in skin 
cancers 
uvb can damage the skin and that damage is related to 
development of cancers 
mattoo said he and a colleague marvin edelman of the weizmann 
institute of science in israel discovered the effect of uvb on 
photosynthesis by studying the level of d1 protein in the duckweed 
plant at different light exposures 
specimens of the plant which grows in water were exposed to 
various wavelengths of light he said the amount of protein found 
in the plants through chemical analysis was then related to the 
amount and type of light exposure 
at a uvb exposure equivalent to noon sunshine mattoo said the 
plant lost half of its d1 protein stores every 30 minutes 
a report on the research will appear this month in the 
proceedings of the national academy of sciences 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

