<TEXT>
the library of congress today opens this 
countrys first big exhibition on alexis de tocqueville who 
finished his classic democracy in america just 150 years ago 
the angloamerican relies upon personal interest to accomplish 
his ends and gives free scope to the unguided exertions and common 
sense of the citizens the russian centers all the authority of 
society in a single arm tocqueville wrote 
the principal instrument of the former is freedom of the 
latter servitude their starting point is different and their 
courses are not the same yet each of them seems to be marked out by 
the will of heaven to sway the destinies of half the globe 
the exhibit which will run until oct 29 is part of a 
frenchamerican commemoration the year 1789 also was marked by the 
proposal of both the us bill of rights and french declaration of 
the rights of man 
one of the 250 items on show is a letter from the marquis de 
lafayette it asks thomas jefferson then us envoy in paris to 
look over the marquis draft of the french declaration 
tocqueville made his first trip to this country at age 25 an 
unpaid apprentice judge who obtained leave to write a study of the 
american prison system 
english was a language not much studied then in france said 
francoise melanio cocurator of the exhibit who is preparing a new 
edition of his work 
but he worked hard on the voyage which took over a month in 
1831 and he did without an interpreter when he got here 
with his friend gustave de beaumont a state prosecutor he 
roamed for 18 months from quebec to new orleans to memphis to green 
bay wis they met the leading americans of the time including 
president andrew jackson 
his book the first part of which was published in 1835 was an 
immediate success it has long been recognized in this country for 
evaluations of the american character and political system 
man is not made for slavery that truth is perhaps even better 
proved by the master than by the slave he wrote almost 30 years 
before abraham lincolns emancipation proclamation 
he did not live to see that dying in 1859 after a political 
career that led him to become minister of foreign affairs his 
political career ended when he was briefly jailed for his opposition 
to the coup by louis napoleon who became napoleon iii 
ms melanio said his preference for decentralized government was 
not popular in france a proposal for decentralization led to 
president charles de gaulles political downfall 20 years ago local 
government has become more popular under president francois 
mitterrand who quoted tocqueville in his speech last month 
celebrating the 200th anniversary of the fall of the bastille 
