<TEXT>
an atlanta judges decision to let a 
quadriplegic turn off machines keeping him alive affirms developing 
legal doctrine that competent people should control their destinies 
say judges and ethics specialists 
but those attending a bioethics conference thursday said such 
decisions are difficult for judges as medical technology advances 
create dilemmas not covered by law 
none of these issues are easy said judge james pudlowski of 
the missouri court of appeals i think these are the most 
difficult types of decisions judges have to make but someone has to 
make them thats why were on the bench 
the missouri appeals court in november overturned a lower court 
opinion and ruled against the family of a braindead women who 
wanted doctors to stop giving her nutrients and let her die the 
case is on appeal to the us supreme court which decided to review 
it 
pudlowski distinguished between the atlanta case of larry james 
mcafee 33 who has been kept alive by machines since a 1985 
motorcycle accident and the braindead womans situation he said 
she can breathe without the use of medical technology while the 
quadriplegics life is being sustained by machine 
we cant say to someone you cant have any more food and 
water pudlowski said there is a distinction 
earlier this week fulton county ga superior court judge 
edward johnson ruled mcafees right to refuse continued 
lifesustaining medical treatment outweighs the states interest in 
preserving his life 
family members and friends testified that mcafee an avid 
