<TEXT>
trade between the united states and 
east germany remains at a trickle and is fraught with obstacles and 
restrictions us executives say 
but many representatives of us companies attending this 
autumns leipzig international trade fair say business ties are on 
the increase and that it is best to get an american foot in the door 
of a market that some day may mushroom 
more than 60 us companies or their european affiliates are 
represented at the eightday trade fair that ends sunday booths 
manned by us companies displayed a variety of products from grains 
to medical supplies 
tom praster a us embassy economics adviser said the major 
problem in useast german trade is the communist countrys lack of 
hard currency 
east germans prefer to barter their own products for westernmade 
goods he said 
countertrading is a big factor in many deals here youve got 
to take something in return and that is often a problem because 
its sometimes hard to find markets for some of the countertrade 
things praster told the ap 
us trade officials say formidible government bureaucracy also 
hampers larger deals 
often the products are purchased by the east german foreign 
trade office and then turned over to the end user when its time to 
service the machine they have to repeat that process praster said 
the people who are using the equipment the hospitals the 
farms or roadbuilding companies cant go directly to the 
manufacturer and ask somebody to come in and repair it 
despite the low volume of trade between the two countries most 
us businesses say their presence at the fair is important 
tom payne a marketing consultant for california raisins says he 
expects the small market for his product in east germany and eastern 
europe to grow 
were here because everybody expects change in the east bloc 
we want to get in on the ground floor 
we believe in time this market can be as good as some of the 
west european countries payne said 
although east germans do sell cheaper raisins imported from 
turkey and iran in regular grocery stores they import highquality 
california raisins to make products for export or for sale in hard 
currency stores at home payne explained 
they use them to make dresdener stollen fruit cakes which 
are exported mostly to western europe but also to the united 
states he said 
but east germany bought only 20 tons of california raisins at 
about 1400 a ton last year its only a small market so far 
its still a development project said payne 
