<TEXT>
attorney general dick thornburgh told skeptical 
lawmakers friday that modeling the justice departments organized 
crime strike forces after antidrug units under the control of 
local us attorneys will put more heat on the mob 
thornburgh said his plan to reorganize the 14 organizedcrime 
strike forces would end bureaucratic turf wars that have hurt 
coordination of federal law enforcement 
to end the turf battles is at the very heart of what the 
president has directed this attorney general to do thornburgh 
told a joint hearing of the senate judiciary and governmental 
affairs committees 
you cant have turf battles when you have only one turf the 
attorney general said 
but thornburgh faced tough questioning about the plan from 
senators mostly democrats who argued that placing the strike 
forces under us attorneys would dilute the justice departments 
commitment to fighting the mob 
sen edward m kennedy dmass said plan will send a clear 
message to the criminal syndicates that the heat is off 
kennedy argued that thornburgh was reorganizing the strike forces 
merely to assuage the egos of us attorneys uneasy about 
justice department lawyers working down the street but not 
accountable to them 
isnt that what this is really about kennedy asked 
thornburgh who was once us attorney in pittsburgh 
its about the uneasiness of an attorney general who doesnt 
feel the best management model is in place thornburgh replied 
thornburgh at one point conceded that local us attorneys 
unwilling to carry out the organizedcrime mission could hurt the 
program 
but the attorney general said he had powers of persuasion to 
exert to remove us attorneys who are not up to snuff 
i believe i have the confidence of the us attorneys i 
believe we are dedicated to the same goal 
the attorney general said the reorganization is designed to deal 
with the changing nature of organized crime since the strike forces 
were set up in 1967 
the traditional mafiastyle crime families have been joined by 
international drug cartels street gangs jamaican posses and other 
organizations he said 
strike force offices have been slow to pick up on these 
emerging groups the attorney general said 
the 13 organized crime drug enforcement task forces set up during 
the reagan administration is the model for this consolidation 
thornburgh said 
the task forces headed by us attorneys were praised this week 
in president bushs drug strategy as a model in interagency 
coordination 
it is significant i believe that this model has been utilized 
to attack our no 1 crime problem drugs rather than the 
independent and separate strike force model thornburgh told the 
lawmakers 
transportation secretary samuel skinner a former us attorney 
in chicago supported the plan saying we will not take the heat 
off organized crime we will increase the heat on organized crime 
but philip b heymann a harvard university law professor who 
headed the justice departments criminal division during the carter 
administration objected to the plan likening it to disassembling 
a racing car and replacing it with an edsel 
thornburgh is barred from doing anything until oct 1 by an 
appropriations bill rider enacted last june that forbids any justice 
department reorganization during the fiscal year which ends sept 
30 
some lawmakers have threatened to extend the ban if thornburgh 
does not agreed to abide by occasional objections to reorganization 
plans a proposition the attorney general rejects 
but sen sam nunn dga an outspoken opponent of the plan 
seemed to signal he wouldnt support a move in congress to block its 
implementation before thornburgh left nunn told the attorney 
general that his permanent investigations subcommittee would closely 
monitor the reorganized strike forces 
nunn who had denounced the proposal when thornburgh unveiled it 
last spring said at the hearing this is the first time i can 
remember that government officials seem determined to reform a 
program that everyone agrees is a tremendous success 
sen strom thurmond rsc who had initially urged thornburgh 
not to merge the strike forces said he now supports the plan 
adding congress should not be in the business of micromanaging 
the department of justice 
</TEXT>
