<TEXT>
the 35 signers of the 1975 helsinki 
agreements on european security have agreed in principle to the 
first exchange of information about their military programs a us 
representative said friday 
john j maresca added however that nato and the warsaw pact 
still disagreed on whether naval and air forces should be included 
maresca is chief us delegate to the 35nation talks on enhancing 
security in europe 
i believe that these negotiations are now well positioned to 
move forward he told fellow negotiators at the beginning of the 
third round of talks however we must be realistic 
the common ground which has emerged over the first two rounds 
can only lead to an early positive conclusion if proposals which are 
unlikely to attract consensus are put aside this will undoubtedly 
be the most difficult task before us he said 
a copy of his speech was made available to the associated press 
soviet negotiators insist that naval and air forces be included 
but nato says they never were meant to be part of the negotiations 
and would further complicate an already complex task 
nobody can conduct a war in europe with naval forces war 
can take place only on land maresca told a news conference after 
the closed negotiating session 
maresca said de facto agreement has been reached in some areas at 
the talks which involve the 16 members of the north atlantic treaty 
organization the sevennation warsaw pact and 12 countries that are 
neutral or profess nonalignment 
running parallel in vienna are natowarsaw pact negotiations on 
reducing conventional forces in europe which resumed thursday 
the principle of a regular exchange of information has now i 
believe been broadly accepted but still to be worked out are how 
to set up a data bank and what information to share on troop 
deployments weapons procurement and other military subjects 
maresca told the reporters 
a breakthrough has been made with acceptance in principle that 
there should be such an exchange he said this represents an 
important step forward which can only have a positive effect on the 
range of arms control talks currently under way 
nato suggested such an exchange at negotiations in early june 
maresca said there also appeared to be agreement in principle for 
a seminar on military policies which he described as the first 
multilateral governmenttogovernment exchange on military policies 
ever held 
