<TEXT>
the united states and south korea reached 
tentative agreement friday on a treaty to end south korean 
harvesting of salmon that us fishermen say has cut into their 
catches off the northwest and alaskan coasts 
the agreement was initialed by negotiators from both nations but 
still has to be formally signed 
it came two weeks after president bush warned the koreans they 
faced a possible ban on shipments of their fishery products to the 
united states if an agreement was not reached by the end of 
september 
earlier this year drift net treaties were negotiated with japan 
and taiwan whose fleets along with the one from south korea fish 
the international waters in the north pacific 
ed wolfe the state departments ambassador for oceans and 
fisheries said the treaties provide for a cooperative enforcement 
program designed to minimize interception of usorigin salmon and 
a cooperative monitoring program designed to assess incidental take 
of a wide variety of marine resources 
under international law only american fishermen are allowed to 
catch salmon spawned in the united states 
the korean agreement grants us enforcement officers 
unrestricted authority to board and inspect korean drift net 
vessels to search for evidence of catches of fish spawned in the 
united states wolfe said 
in addition all korean drift net vessels will have to be 
equipped with satellite transponders by the 1990 fishing season 
these would allow us officials to keep track of the location of 
vessels to ensure they dont fish outside designated areas 
in exchange the koreans will be allowed to fish an expanded area 
of the north pacific in may 
more than 700 vessels from japan korean and taiwan have been 
using drift nets in the north pacific ostensibly to catch squid 
but us fishing groups claim they are actually fishing for 
salmon that spawn in north america and swim the pacific ocean 
salmon runs in alaska washington state and oregon have already 
suffered as a result of the catches the american groups say 
environmentalists also complain that use of the drift nets which 
they call walls of death result in the deaths of thousands of 
marine mammals and seabirds annually 
</TEXT>
