<TEXT>
a year after radiocarbon tests found the shroud of 
turin to be only 700 years old a participant in a shroud symposium 
said friday the bright light of the resurrection may have altered 
the aging process 
many of the questions boil down to this said jacques evin 
an engineer at the radiocarbon laboratory of lyon in the event of 
the resurrection of christ would there have been a sufficient burst 
of light to alter the process of carbon decay 
the paris international scientific symposium on the shroud of 
turin gave shroudies dedicated students of what is purported 
to be the burial cloth of jesus christ their first chance to 
contest the findings issued in october 1988 
it is a most unusual object and its an object that means a lot 
of things to a lot of people said professor michael tite of the 
british museum research laboratory at the end of the twoday 
gathering anything you do with it is bound to cause controversy 
tite was at the heart of the debate last year he headed one of 
three laboratories that said the shroud was made about 700 years 
ago 13 centuries after the death of christ scientific teams from 
the university of arizona and university of zurich also participated 
rather than resolving questions of the shrouds authenticity the 
radiocarbon tests appear to have become a new source of argument 
the 14yardlong cloth bears a faint yellowish negative image of 
the front and back of a man with thorn marks on the head 
lacerations from flogging on the back and bruises on the shoulders 
suggestive of accounts of christs crucifixion 
it has been kept in italys cathedral of turin since the middle 
ages when creation of false religious relics was widespread the 
nowretired roman catholic cardinal there anastasio ballestrero 
invited scientists last year to test samples the size of postage 
stamps with radiocarbon dating techniques 
datings by the laboratories ranged from 1260 to 1390 ballestrero 
eventually endorsed the results but said the shrouds significance 
as an object of deep religious faith was unchanged 
few symposium participants contested the test results but evin 
and others questioned whether the cloth had been altered somehow to 
produce an inaccurate reading 
tite was skeptical of evins theory 
it seems to me a slight coincidence that if there was a burst 
of radiation it would have been just enough to date the cloth to 
the 14th century he said 
some of the 100 spectators cheered when one of their number 
insisted the scientists had tested a piece of the cloth near a seam 
that was restored in the 16th or 17th century 
we do not have a pure specimen he declared it was 
contaminated there were threads from the 16th century extending 
into the main part of the shroud i think we may be dealing with a 
clever forger who rewove the threads 
tite said the results would have been affected only if 6070 
percent of the cloth were rewoven 
john jackson 43 of colorado springs colo said density 
measurements of the frontal image on the cloth appear to show a body 
was lifted through it but he stopped well short of calling the 
phenomenon evidence of the resurrection 
i dont want to get into too much speculation on the religious 
implications said jackson who has studied the shroud for 15 
years if the shroud is medieval then this image was formed then 
im also open to the fact that if someone else can explain this 
image in a conventional way then that should take priority over 
mine 
</TEXT>
