<TEXT>
us marines conducted reconnaissance 
exercises friday in a resumption of military maneuvers the 
government claims violate the panama canal treaties 
nearly 130 marines rode 13 armored vehicles through several small 
towns west of panama city near the rodman naval base 
we are exercising our rights and obligations unde the canal 
treaties by reconnoitering the high ground west and south of 
arraijan said col jj doyle commander of marine forces in the 
us southern command which is based in panama 
the southern command had suspended exercises on panamanian soil 
for three weeks 
doyle said the exercises were conducted on panamanian soil to 
explore several hills because we are responsible for defending 
the canal 
he said the panamanian defense forces were advised of the 
exercise four days in advance and were asked to provide an escort 
no escort was visible 
civilians waved at the marines who waved back when the armored 
vehicles drove through towns no incidents were reported 
a panamanian army lieutenant who identified himself as a rangel 
in command at arraijan said the us military was violating the 
1977 treaties under which the canal is to be turned over to panama 
by the year 2000 
conflicting interpretations of treaty terms have caused friction 
between the us military and panamanian government the united 
states claims the right to conduct operations on panamanian soil as 
part of its commitment to defend the canal 
several confrontations have taken place in the past two months 
on aug 9 panamanians arrested two us military policemen and us 
army units blocked the entrance to fort amador arrested two 
panamanian soldiers and held them until the americans were freed 
