<TEXT>
on sept 30 1987 wright investors service 
published a rare special report warning that stocks were overpriced 
and headed for a sharp and substantial decline 
in some ways said wright an international firm based in 
bridgeport conn the current situation is comparable to that 
which preceded the great stock market crash of 1929 
barely two weeks later on oct 19 1987 the market collapsed 
again 
this week wright issued another special report to document our 
view that a stock market correction one stopping far short of the 
decline witnessed two years ago but significant nevertheless does 
indeed lie ahead 
the firm which handles portfolios in the billions of dollars and 
advises the trust departments of many banks prides itself on 
objective analysis rather than opinion which is often the staple of 
brokerage house forecasts 
in 1987 for example it observed that the priceearnings ratio 
of the standard amp poors composite index was exceptionally high at 
22 higher even than the 199 prior to the 1929 crash and it noted 
that the dividend yield of the sampp 500stock index of 26 percent 
was approaching the 3 percent of 1929 
this weeks report offers this rationale 
1 stock prices are too high relative to both historical 
valuations and the current level of interest rates 
2 the us economy is in the process of slowing 
3 corporate profit growth is about to come to a halt 
conclusion this combination of factors suuggests to us that a 
significant reversal of the stock markets recent gains may be under 
way before 1989 is over 
partly obscuring the current vulnerability wright says is the 
fact that priceearnings ratios at 14 are not exceptionally high 
still they are higher than the post1950 average of 12 based on 
the sampp 500stock index 
what happens when profits decline already wright points out 
growth of real profits after taxes excluding profits from 
inventory inflation and adjusted for depreciation have slowed 14 
percent from the 1986 peak 
the special report states that stock prices appear in their worst 
light when matched against corporate book values both the dow jones 
industrial average and the sampp 500 are now priced at 24 times book 
value 
wright comments that since 1930 the market has been priced 
higher relative to book value only once in the summer of 1987 just 
before the stock market crash 
while some analysts minimize the significance of book values 
some of which have been distorted by corporate repurchases of 
shares wright calls attention to a recurring phenomenon for 40 
years two times book value has put a ceiling on prices 
such factors become even more significant as the economy slows 
adjusted for inflation retail sales are only 1 percent ahead of 
last years pace factory orders are down manufacturing activity 
has leveled off 
wright also refers to the money supply in support of its 
conclusions despite recent easing the money supply fell 25 
percent in the year ended june 1989 since 1954 declines of that 
magnitude have been followed by recession 
corporate profits offer little support for the market already 
profit growth has slowed real profits after taxes excluding 
profits from inventory inflation and adjusted for depreciation are 
well below their peaks 
since 1986 wright observes real corporate profits from 
operations have declined 14 percent in its opinion further 
deterioration is likely 
since stocks often interact with the level of interest rates on 
bonds wright examined that too and found it negative 
to bring stock and bond prices into relationship with averages 
over the 19691988 period wright believes one or a combination of 
these would have to occur 
1 a corporate earnings rise unlikely of 12 percent to 15 
percent 
2 a reduction of bond yields by about one full percentage point 
3 a fall off in stock prices of more than 10 percent 
in summary wright is telling clients that the returns on stocks 
are likely to be negative over the next 12 to 18 months and that 
they might be better off in longterm bonds 
by then the old relationships of the various averages are likely 
to be restored then wright says we anticipate the start of a 
new bull market 
</TEXT>
