i think each parent ought to determine whats best for her 
child said mrs hennigan who teaches a fifthgrade class for 
gifted and talented students in suburban virginia 
at least where public schools are concerned the age at which a 
child begins his education is becoming as controversial as 
parental choice a centerpiece of president bushs education 
initiatives that would let parents decide which public school their 
child would attend 
some educators are convinced that youngsters will be more 
successful in school if they are 5 starting kindergarten others 
scoff at the notion of arbitrary age limits and favor flexible 
curricula for various maturity levels 
we agree there is a problem in that young children are not 
succeeding in kindergarten and first grade as they should but the 
problem is with the curriculum and the strategy in the way children 
are asked to learn what is inappropriate with their age group 
said barbara willer of the national association for the education of 
young children 
susan dranitzke an educational consultant who advises parents on 
their childrens school readiness said kindergarten is more like 
first grade used to be at this point the way public kindergartens 
are its probably better to have them older 
to be eligible for public school kindergartens 23 states now 
require children to be 5 years old by sept 2 ten years ago most 
states allowed youngsters to begin kindergarten if their fifth 
birthday would fall as late as november december or january 
complicating the situation for parents in five states are laws 
requiring that their children attend kindergarten those states are 
arkansas delaware rhode island south carolina and west virginia 
the district of columbia and the adjacent maryland counties of 
prince georges and montgomery have held to the dec 31 kindergarten 
eligibility date in virginia the cutoff has been moved to sept 
30 but children with later birthdays can be tested to determine if 
they are emotionally physically and intellectually ready for 
kindergarten 
david elkind professor of child study at tufts university in 
medford mass and the author of the hurried child said 
raising the entry age of children is merely a policy solution to a 
people problem and policy solutions to people problems never work 
the need is for flexible programs in kindergarten and first grades 
raising the age is not going to do anything except raise the 
curriculum he explained we need to recognize what children are 
like at that stage and then match the curriculum to the child 
indianas new school entry age law kicks in this year with a 
september cutoff date that moves up to june 1 by the 199293 school 
year 
we are not letting our kids grow up we are pushing them and i 
dont know why said rep esther wilson a thirdgrade teacher and 
state legislator who wrote and pushed through indianas law after 
nearly six years of work 
with this bill i predict the dropout rate is going to be down 
because the majority of our boys and girls will be socially and 
emotionally ready for school said wilson 
tom schultz project director for early childhood education at 
the national associaton of state boards of education said raising 
the entry age results in a problem of equity in terms of what the 
experiences will be during that extra year out of school 
by merely raising the entry age schultz said a group of kids 
who would have gone to kindergarten will sit in a preschool at home 
or at day care another year parents vary in their aility to pay for 
and provide stimulus 
we need to help teachers find ways to deal with student 
diversity he said 
one solution schultz said would be to allow children to enter 
school the month they become 5 the problem with that he added is 
that it would be difficult for teachers to adjust to new kids 
continually arriving 
another idea is cooperative learning which places a child in 
a group of youngsters with abilities similar to his own assignments 
are given to the groups so that youngsters can teach each other as 
they work together 
susan sweitzer of the gesell institute a private educational 
organization in new haven conn said 1518 percent of more than 
16000 school districts around the nation use gesells procedures to 
assess young childrens readiness to learn 
when these procedures are properly used she said school systems 
can determine which approach is suited to the needs of a particular 
child either the traditional lockstep grade system or 
alternative programs that insert a transitional year for children to 
mature before or after first grade 
i used to feel pretty strongly that the cutoff date should be 
sept 1 or aug 31 but i have really grown to an opinion of 
encouraging districts to create options from which parents can 
choose so it doesnt really matter when the cutoff date is ms 
sweitzer said 
regardless of when a child is enrolled in kindergarten all 
states require that by a certain age children must be in first 
grade in no state however is that required date set so early 
that parents do not have the freedom to delay their youngsters 
entry into kindergarten said ms weller of the national association 
for the education of young children 
