<TEXT>
a coalition of environmentalists religious 
groups and investors has established a code of conduct by which 
corporations can be judged on how responsible they are toward the 
environment 
building on guidelines set 12 years ago to judge corporate 
actions in south africa the 10point valdez principles annunced 
thursday call on companies to address the effects of both their 
product and production processes on employees communities and the 
environment 
the code of conduct named after the alaskan oil spill by the 
exxon valdez tanker also asks companies to appoint environmental 
experts to their boards of directors and publicize an annual audit 
of compliance with the code 
as i talked to people this winter about this idea it was like 
striking a match to flint said joan bavaria a cochairwoman of 
the coalition and the president of franklin research and 
development a boston research firm 
bavaria told the new york times that funds that base their 
investments on social values consistently find the environment to be 
the single largest concern of their clients 
in the long term the coalition believes the most profitable 
companies are those that are willing to forego shortterm profits 
and invest according to environmental and social concerns 
the coalition for environmentally responsible economies recently 
brought pressure against exxon corp to name a director with 
environmental knowledge to its board 
the coalition is a step to bring investors who control about 100 
billion in pension funds and other vehicles together with social 
action groups that have large memberships but often lack leverage 
with corporations 
it includes the social investment forum of 325 fund managers and 
investment advisers the national council of churches interfaith 
center on corporate responsibility and 14 environmental groups 
the environmental code was inspired in part by the sullivan 
principles formed in 1977 to recommended corporate conduct for 
firms operating in racially segregated south africa 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

