<TEXT>
like a parent scolding an ungrateful child a 
federal financing agency has warned the tennessee valley authority 
that if it sells bonds to the public it can never come back home 
the tva the federal agency that supplies electricity to many 
parts of the south is debating whether to float bonds in the public 
market for the first time in 15 years 
but if it goes ahead with its plan to sell a huge 65 billion 
issue on wall street to refinance old highinterest notes the 
federal financing bank says it never again will loan tva its 
lowcost funds 
the federal financing bank is an arm of the treasury department 
that loans money to federal agencies such as the us postal 
service the exportimport bank and the rural electrification 
administration by buying bonds that they issue 
the bond purchases are like a private loan to the agencies since 
the financing bank keeps the bonds and receives all the interest 
paid on them their advantage is lower interest rates than those of 
bonds sold on the public market 
tva wants to pay off bonds from the financing bank that carry 
interest rates averaging about 1225 percent it says it should be 
able to float new publicmarket bonds at about 9 percent or lower 
reflecting how much interest rates have dropped since the bonds were 
bought 
the refinancing should save tva about 100 million a year for the 
next 20 years said william f malec chief financial officer of the 
knoxville tennbased agency which is the nations largest power 
company 
that in turn should help tva hold down its electric rates tva 
established by congress in 1933 to help develop the rural south 
sells power at wholesale rates to municipal and cooperative power 
companies in seven states that serve about 3 million households 
tva has borrowed exclusively from the financing bank since that 
agencys creation in 1974 and it owes it about 165 billion tva 
also has about 15 billion in public debt outstanding that was sold 
before 1974 
tvas malec decided to go to the public market for refinancing 
after the federal financing bank declined to loan it fresh money at 
lower rates ahead of the call dates of the existing bonds which are 
several years away 
but the financing bank made clear late last month in a letter to 
tva that it no longer would loan tva money should it go that route 
were in a situation where the ffb is under no requirement to 
lend to us malec said 
however malec said last week the decision over floating public 
bonds may not be that tough because the cost of the financing 
agencys funds is not substantially lower than the rate the tva 
could get in the public market 
another factor in favor of public borrowing is that it would 
allow the tva to structure bonds in more favorable terms such as 
allowing them to be called earlier than the federal bonds should 
interest rates drop 
malec said the tva expects to make its decision in a few weeks 
in the meantime us sen albert gore jr dtenn and other 
members of the tennessee congressional delegation say they will try 
to persuade the financing bank to change its stance 
theres little question tva bonds would receive a warm welcome 
from the credit market tvas old public debt holds the top rating 
from the major creditrating agencies also 17 investment houses 
submitted proposals to help bring new notes to market malec said 
of these five were selected with first boston corp chosen as lead 
underwriter 
