<TEXT>
dallas ap a federal judges preliminary ruling could spell 
trouble for the federal governments seizure of a number of texas 
banks including mcorp and texas american bancshares inc 
in preliminary findings issued last week us district judge 
robert porter ruled the federal deposit insurance corp had acted 
illegally in seizing 17 million owed to one of the five banks still 
owned by mcorp once the secondlargest bank holding company in 
texas 
the ruling came in a suit brought by mcorps bank in new 
braunfels and does not involve the parent company said mcorp 
spokesman joe stroop 
nevertheless stroop said mcorp has a suit pending before porter 
which makes some of the same assertions 
at issue is whether federal regulators acted properly in refusing 
to return to some otherwise solvent banks funds they had on deposit 
in insolvent sister institutions 
regulators fully repaid other creditors and porter said the fdic 
acted illegally because federal banking law requires it to treat all 
creditors equally when a bank failed 
it is still just a preliminary ruling and the judge has asked 
for additional information fdic deputy general counsel mark rosen 
said 
still the opinion could be used to decide larger cases dallas 
attorney david bryant said 
we feel strongly it is the correct ruling and that none of the 
courts that look at it will find differently said bryant an 
attorney for mcorp 
the government seized 20 of mcorps 25 banks last march 
eventually selling them to banc one corp mcorps suit claims 12 of 
those 20 were illegally forced into insolvency by the governments 
action regulators have estimated the rescue will be the second most 
expensive in the nations history 
similarly texas american bancshares has sued the fdic claiming 
some of the 24 banks seized were improperly made insolvent 
