<TEXT>
energy futures prices rose sharply in brisk 
trading friday supported by internal market influences and reports 
suggesting demand for oil is strong 
crude prices which got a lift from strength in the gasoline 
market broke through what analysts said was a key technical barrier 
of 1950 
on the new york mercantile exchange the october contract for 
west texas intermediate the benchmark grade of us crude oil 
jumped 34 cents to close at 1975 a barrel after rising 13 cents in 
the previous session 
wholesale unleaded gasoline for october delivery gained 146 
cents a gallon to finish at 5709 cents a gallon while heating oil 
for delivery next month advanced 124 cents to 5674 cents a gallon 
analysts attributed much of the buying activity to technical 
factors but some activity in the crude pits stemmed from price 
fundamentals they said 
people are buying crude because its underpriced in relation to 
gasoline said james steel an analyst with refco inc so 
refiners will keep buying in order to turn it into gasoline at a 
profit 
reports this week from the american petroleum institute and the 
department of energy on weekly inventories continued to be bullish 
for the oil market because they suggested that demand remains 
strong said madison galbraith senior energy specialist with 
merrill lynch energy futures 
the api reported a 58 millionbarrel reduction in gasoline 
stocks and a 15 millionbarrel drawdown in crude stocks the drop 
in gasoline inventories was larger than the market had expected 
while the crude figure was in line with projections 
the market is being driven by good fundamental support 
galbraith said demand is better than anyone expected and crude 
has broken through a key 1950 barrier 
energy brokers said rumors also added some spark to fridays 
market including unsubstantiated reports of problems at some us 
refineries 
gasoline futures benefited earlier this week from concerns about 
possible tightening in supplies after a fire at shell oil cos 
martinez calif refinery and one at ashland petroleum cos 
refinery in st paul park minn 
an unfounded rumor circulated in the financial and oil markets 
that soviet leader mikhail gorbachev had died but analysts said 
that had nothing to to with a late surge in oil futures prices the 
rumor was denied by the white house and soviet embassy in washington 
we heard that rumor but did not see any of our clients buy 
based on that rumor said larry lawrence manager of options and 
technical analysis for elders futures inc this was not a big news 
day and people did not expect the strength in prices so people are 
stretching for reasons 
